gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/7834D4B9-D87D-4382-9C03-AF6DBC7573A2"><gtr:id>7834D4B9-D87D-4382-9C03-AF6DBC7573A2</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Lucy</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>O'Shea</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH008772%2F1"><gtr:id>D0DF3591-03DD-48F4-8958-CB16E0235A6D</gtr:id><gtr:title>Examining the variation in household recycling rates across the UK</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H008772/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Recycling rates vary considerably across local authorities in the UK. This research seeks to address why this is the case. Previous research on recycling has identified 'push' factors, such as household size and composition as being important, as well as 'pull' factors, such as the existence of kerbside recycling. The analysis will show whether there is a 'local authority effect', as well as focusing on the capacity to recycle, which together with household demand for recycling might explain why the UK languishes in 11th position in terms of recycling performance across the EU15 countries. The methodology will consist of a theoretical explanation of the factors driving recycling rates and an empirical analysis using econometric techniques that can identify the key factors which are significant in influencing recycling performance across local authorities. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-07-25</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-10-26</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>80364</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gt