tal behaviour generally.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>0529F401-1FD0-4F8D-9133-57F43F148517</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Energy,Environment,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:areas/><gtr:description>Dorset waste management partnership</gtr:description><gtr:geographicReach>Local/Municipal/Regional</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>3A17FFF3-ACD8-4302-B3A0-1B5BB6D4E7C3</gtr:id><gtr:type>Citation in other policy documents</gtr:type></gtr:policyInfluenceOutput></gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutput><gtr:description>The data base consists of waste, recycling and socioeconomic data at the level of the local authority for all of the UK. Source data used to construct the dataset were taken from the WasteDataFlow website, a web-based system for municipal waste data reporting by UK local authorities to government, where they are used by the Department for Environmental and Rural Affairs (DEFRA) and other departments to produce statistics. Office for National Statistics data on regional socio-economic characteristics were also used.</gtr:description><gtr:id>0A83FE0D-17F9-4D04-9D9A-E93A64AB02F6</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The database is instrumental in driving our research forward. On the basis of analysis of the data we were able to ascertain the existence of an inverse relationship between recycling and frequency of bin collections. This was picked up both by interested academics as well as practitioners and our work informed work into streamlining waste management practices of the Dorset Waste Management Partnership.</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>Examining the Variation in Household Recycling Rates across the United Kingdom</gtr:title><gtr:type>Database/Collection of data</gtr:type><g